talk about where we are right
now with version 3.2 and what's

00:02:36.120 --> 00:02:38.280
coming up next with Snow Leopard.

00:02:38.380 --> 00:02:42.240
So let's start off and talk
about software distribution.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.440
So we have a feature
called Install Package,

00:02:45.460 --> 00:02:48.140
lets you install
packages on your clients.

00:02:48.170 --> 00:02:51.260
We have a feature called Auto Install,
which allows you to install packages

00:02:51.620 --> 00:02:54.420
on machines that are both on the
network and off the network using

00:02:54.420 --> 00:02:57.870
a server that's always on that will
be able to contact those systems.

00:02:57.960 --> 00:02:59.720
We have -- I'm going to talk
a little bit more about that

00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:00.740
in detail in just a moment.

00:03:01.380 --> 00:03:05.370
We also have a File Copy command
and Delete Files.

00:03:05.430 --> 00:03:08.310
So digging a little bit
more into Auto Install.

00:03:08.430 --> 00:03:11.030
So the scenario here is you have
machines that are both on the network

00:03:11.030 --> 00:03:14.360
and off the network and you need
to get packages installed onto them.

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:16.270
And the best way to do this is to
have a server that's -- a machine

00:03:16.270 --> 00:03:19.340
that's going to act as a server
for you that's always running.

00:03:19.340 --> 00:03:23.270
And you install another copy of
Remote Desktop onto that machine.

00:03:23.570 --> 00:03:26.840
and you configure your
administrator to use that.

00:03:26.850 --> 00:03:29.330
We call that a task server and you
configure your administrator to use

00:03:29.330 --> 00:03:31.040
that machine as your task server.

00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:34.710
And you select your package on your
administrator and it delegates that

00:03:34.710 --> 00:03:38.110
package over to the task server to
complete the installation for it,

00:03:38.290 --> 00:03:42.010
copies the package over there and
the task server then contacts all the

00:03:42.070 --> 00:03:46.030
clients and installs the package on all
the clients that are currently online.

00:03:46.090 --> 00:03:49.960
If you have a machine that's
offline like this MacBook Pro,

00:03:49.990 --> 00:03:53.430
once that machine comes online,
it's going to contact the task server

00:03:53.750 --> 00:03:57.410
and then the package is going to get
installed on that machine as well.

00:03:58.300 --> 00:04:01.590
Let's talk about the
asset management features.

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:04.100
We have software reports,
hardware reports,

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:07.600
application usage reports,
and user history reports.

00:04:07.670 --> 00:04:12.340
And you can run these reports on all
machines that are online at any time.

00:04:12.410 --> 00:04:14.920
And you can also,
by setting a report cache

00:04:15.270 --> 00:04:19.740
generation policy on your clients,
have these reports generated

00:04:19.740 --> 00:04:22.740
on a regular basis and uploaded
to a task server machine,

00:04:22.750 --> 00:04:25.980
just like what I talked about
a moment ago with auto install.

00:04:26.090 --> 00:04:31.000
You can also export the data into a
tab format or a cum-delimited file.

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:34.670
And we also have a remote spotlight
search feature that allows you

00:04:34.730 --> 00:04:38.710
to search the spotlight databases
on all your client machines.

00:04:39.870 --> 00:04:44.210
So let's talk a little bit more about
how the offline reporting works.

00:04:44.340 --> 00:04:48.980
So just like with auto install,
it's best if you have a machine

00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:51.140
that's going to act as a server and
it's going to be on all the time

00:04:51.140 --> 00:04:54.140
and you install another copy of
your remote desktop on that machine.

00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:56.570
You don't have to have the admin running,
you just have to have

00:04:56.650 --> 00:04:57.860
the software installed.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.570
Then you configure your admin
console to use that task server.

00:05:02.830 --> 00:05:06.500
Then you set a reporting policy for all
your clients so that they'll generate

00:05:06.500 --> 00:05:10.900
these report caches on a regular basis
and upload them up to the task server.

00:05:11.240 --> 00:05:12.800
Once those reports are
on the task server,

00:05:12.800 --> 00:05:17.630
your admin can then run its reports and
it'll get the report data from the admin.

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:21.090
The advantage of setting up this
offline reporting is that even if

00:05:21.090 --> 00:05:24.200
one of your clients is offline,
you can still get reports.

00:05:27.010 --> 00:05:30.300
Let's talk about the remote
administration features.

00:05:30.310 --> 00:05:33.860
So we have a send Unix command so you can
send Unix commands or Unix scripts to all

00:05:33.860 --> 00:05:36.440
your machines and get the results back.

00:05:36.440 --> 00:05:40.540
We have a set startup disk that allows
you to set the startup disk to a

00:05:40.540 --> 00:05:43.300
local volume or to a network volume.

00:05:43.310 --> 00:05:44.950
We have various system control features.

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:48.860
You can sleep, wake, restart,
shut down a machine, empty the trash,

00:05:48.860 --> 00:05:50.440
lock and unlock the screens.

00:05:50.450 --> 00:05:54.030
We have some user control features
that allow you to log out users or open

00:05:54.030 --> 00:05:56.460
files for them or open applications.

00:05:56.480 --> 00:05:59.550
And we also have a lights out management
feature for X servers that support

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:03.820
this that allow you to restart,
power on or shut down a machine

00:06:03.820 --> 00:06:05.060
regardless of the OS state.

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:07.480
So even if the machine
is kernel panicked,

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:09.130
you can still restart it.

00:06:10.380 --> 00:06:12.870
So let's talk about remote assistance.

00:06:12.950 --> 00:06:15.340
You can observe or
control a remote screen.

00:06:15.620 --> 00:06:19.010
You can also observe many
screens at once in a single view.

00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:22.000
You can share your screen out
to a number of other machines.

00:06:22.040 --> 00:06:26.860
We have a guest access mode that allows
the end user to either allow or deny a

00:06:26.860 --> 00:06:29.230
control request from an administrator.

00:06:29.300 --> 00:06:33.260
We have a full screen mode so you
can see the other user's machine

00:06:33.260 --> 00:06:35.060
on full screen on your machine.

00:06:35.130 --> 00:06:39.830
We have a curtain mode that blocks
anyone from seeing what's going on on the

00:06:39.830 --> 00:06:43.160
machine that you're remotely controlling.

00:06:43.220 --> 00:06:46.760
You can drag and drop files for
copying using screen control.

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:51.470
And you can also get or
send the pasteboard buffer.

00:06:51.860 --> 00:06:55.100
We also have a widget for doing
remote desktop observation

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:56.800
or screen observation.

00:06:56.850 --> 00:07:01.050
And there's an interactive text
messaging client as well for environments

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:03.920
that aren't appropriate for iChat.

00:07:04.890 --> 00:07:07.100
Let's talk about automation.

00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:10.830
We have a rich Apple script dictionary,
lots of automator actions,

00:07:10.830 --> 00:07:14.780
and just about any management command
in the product can be scheduled.

00:07:16.250 --> 00:07:18.690
and lastly all the setup
and configuration features

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:19.840
for Remote Desktop.

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:22.190
We have task templates so you can
put all your favorite settings for

00:07:22.190 --> 00:07:26.180
your tasks and when you create tasks
later you can easily populate that

00:07:26.280 --> 00:07:28.040
task document with your settings.

00:07:28.080 --> 00:07:31.940
We have labels so you can label your
machines much like you would label,

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.080
set a label on a file in the finder.

00:07:34.130 --> 00:07:37.790
We have user defined list views so
you can create your own list with

00:07:37.790 --> 00:07:41.780
a set of machines from your library
and set what kind of information

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:45.080
you want to see in that list,
for instance what version of the

00:07:45.110 --> 00:07:47.410
operating system it's running,
how much RAM it's got.

00:07:47.560 --> 00:07:51.440
You can also create smart computer
lists that will filter your entire

00:07:51.540 --> 00:07:53.660
library using some of this criteria.

00:07:53.660 --> 00:07:55.460
For instance,
create a list that shows you

00:07:55.460 --> 00:07:58.860
all the machines that have
less than one gigabyte of RAM.

00:07:58.860 --> 00:08:01.600
And then you can create
groups to organize your,

00:08:01.600 --> 00:08:05.790
the tasks that you've created and
the computer lists you've created.

00:08:05.910 --> 00:08:08.400
In addition to this,
we have a user mode for the

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:12.010
Remote Desktop application so
that you can let unprivileged

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:15.740
users run it and you can restrict
what features they have access to.

00:08:15.780 --> 00:08:18.640
We have network scanners for finding
machines on your network for you

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:19.960
to add to your computer library.

00:08:20.230 --> 00:08:23.730
We have directory-based authentication
and a setup assistant that

00:08:23.730 --> 00:08:26.410
allows you to configure some
of the more advanced client-side

00:08:26.410 --> 00:08:29.380
features from the admin console.

00:08:30.310 --> 00:08:32.740
So Remote Desktop 3.2
is the current version.

00:08:32.740 --> 00:08:35.130
It was released in October of 2007.

00:08:35.230 --> 00:08:38.800
It brings Leopard compatibility,
greatly improved screen

00:08:38.800 --> 00:08:41.920
sharing performance,
greatly improved keyboard

00:08:41.920 --> 00:08:45.340
mapping for screen control,
as well as improved

00:08:45.340 --> 00:08:47.600
file copy reliability.

00:08:48.170 --> 00:08:50.560
and what's coming up next
is Remote Desktop 3.3.

00:08:50.560 --> 00:08:53.900
It's gonna be a free
upgrade to existing users.

00:08:53.960 --> 00:08:56.230
And I'm gonna talk about all
the things that we're gonna be

00:08:56.230 --> 00:08:57.520
improving with this version.

00:08:57.660 --> 00:09:02.440
So first off is improved management
for offline reporting settings.

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:05.750
And I talked about the offline reporting
settings just a moment ago when I was

00:09:05.750 --> 00:09:10.530
talking about how it's advantageous to
have your clients generate these caches

00:09:10.570 --> 00:09:13.780
and upload them to their task server
so you can do your reports at any time.

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:17.920
So first thing I'm gonna talk
about how things work right now.

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:22.900
On the left side is the preference
pane in Remote Desktop that shows you

00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:26.200
where the settings are for setting
your default reporting policies.

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:30.750
So currently, this is in the same
tab as the task server.

00:09:31.360 --> 00:09:34.630
Now the truth of what the
reporting policy is on each

00:09:34.690 --> 00:09:37.330
client is set on the admin.

00:09:37.330 --> 00:09:42.250
And what that means is that if you
have a client that is generating a

00:09:42.250 --> 00:09:48.780
report that you don't want to do and you
remove the preferences on that client,

00:09:48.780 --> 00:09:52.110
the next time the administrator
that had originally set up that

00:09:52.110 --> 00:09:56.830
policy authenticates to that client,
it's going to push that schedule

00:09:56.980 --> 00:09:58.200
back down again and you're
going to have the same issue.

00:09:58.380 --> 00:10:01.390
Now also from your administrator console,
you don't have any visibility

00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:06.100
into what other report policies
other administrators have set up.

00:10:07.030 --> 00:10:10.330
So in the next version,
we're going to move the reporting

00:10:10.380 --> 00:10:13.350
settings out of the Task Server tab
and into its own tab so that

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:15.750
they're a lot more discoverable.

00:10:16.370 --> 00:10:19.940
We're going to move the truth of
the offline reporting policy onto

00:10:19.940 --> 00:10:21.500
the client rather than on the admin.

00:10:21.540 --> 00:10:24.010
So if you have a client
that is generating reports

00:10:24.110 --> 00:10:27.180
that you don't want it to,
you can delete the preferences and you

00:10:27.180 --> 00:10:30.890
don't have to worry about another rogue
administrator pushing that policy back

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.170
down to the administrator and getting
the reports generated all over again.

00:10:35.790 --> 00:10:38.730
and the next thing that we're
going to change is we're going to

00:10:38.740 --> 00:10:39.790
have a single reporting policy.

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:43.000
No longer are we going to have
different reporting policies

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:43.890
coming from different admins.

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:47.400
We're going to have a single reporting
policy that all administrators

00:10:47.400 --> 00:10:49.470
can view and set the settings on.

00:10:49.480 --> 00:10:51.820
So everyone will be able
to see the same policy.

00:10:51.820 --> 00:10:55.460
Also,
this is the computer get info window.

00:10:55.460 --> 00:10:58.560
You see that you see all
the administrators who can

00:10:58.560 --> 00:10:59.760
manage this machine now.

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:03.380
And not only that,
but you also see who is interested

00:11:03.380 --> 00:11:06.700
in getting these offline reports
loaded up to their task server.

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:09.750
And you see what task server
is associated with each

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:10.800
of these administrators.

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:13.940
So this is all new in 3.3.

00:11:14.140 --> 00:11:19.090
So the next thing that we're going
to improve is our NAT support.

00:11:20.310 --> 00:11:26.370
So in the current version,
Remote Desktop only allows,

00:11:26.510 --> 00:11:30.070
each machine has to have a unique
IP address and the reason is that

00:11:30.070 --> 00:11:34.000
it hard codes the port that it
communicates to the client on,

00:11:34.010 --> 00:11:34.780
3283.

00:11:34.920 --> 00:11:39.240
So that means that behind a NAT,
currently, you can only have one machine

00:11:39.260 --> 00:11:40.670
for it to the WAN side.

00:11:40.680 --> 00:11:44.100
So in the next version,
we're going to allow the administrator

00:11:44.100 --> 00:11:47.920
to have machines with the same
IP address but with different ports.

00:11:48.070 --> 00:11:52.340
So now you can configure your NAT router
to port forward to all your machines

00:11:52.340 --> 00:11:55.430
behind it and just with different ports.

00:11:57.870 --> 00:12:01.290
So while it's great that you
can now manually configure your

00:12:01.370 --> 00:12:05.600
NAT router and manually enter in
these ports into Remote Desktop,

00:12:05.600 --> 00:12:09.320
in some environments it may be even
better to have this happen automatically.

00:12:09.400 --> 00:12:13.870
And you can do this if you have
a supported UPnP NAT router and

00:12:13.870 --> 00:12:18.790
you configure a client to register
its network services into a wide

00:12:18.790 --> 00:12:23.970
area of Bonjour Server which
you can configure using Leopard.

00:12:24.150 --> 00:12:30.120
and when you do that,
the client is going to learn what the

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:35.060
WAN side of the port is that got opened
up automatically using UPnP and it's

00:12:35.060 --> 00:12:37.990
going to register that information
in the wide area Bonjour server.

00:12:38.160 --> 00:12:43.100
Now your Remote Desktop Administrator
using a Bonjour scanner and also looking

00:12:43.100 --> 00:12:48.760
at that same wide area Bonjour server is
going to learn what the wide area dynamic

00:12:48.760 --> 00:12:52.800
port is that was set up and then without
any other additional configuration,

00:12:52.800 --> 00:12:57.840
it's going to be able to connect to
that client behind your UPnP NAT router.

00:12:57.890 --> 00:13:03.880
And it will also as needed,
re-resolve that DNS address,

00:13:03.950 --> 00:13:06.800
that wide area Bonjour address so it
will always be able to find that client.

00:13:06.830 --> 00:13:09.670
So even if the dynamic
port mapping changes,

00:13:09.670 --> 00:13:14.390
Remote Desktop will still be able
to re-resolve and find that machine.

00:13:15.430 --> 00:13:20.160
So in addition to improving
the offline reporting settings

00:13:20.630 --> 00:13:23.530
and improving our NAT settings,
we're also going to have support for

00:13:23.530 --> 00:13:25.620
managing machines across back to my Mac.

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:29.350
We're going to add support
for IPv6 addresses.

00:13:29.720 --> 00:13:36.420
And just like as 3.2 came in Leopard,
3.3 is going to come in Snow Leopard.

00:13:36.500 --> 00:13:39.460
So just as a review,
3.2 is the current version.

00:13:39.460 --> 00:13:40.390
It's out right now.

00:13:40.670 --> 00:13:44.200
3.3 is going to be our next
update with Snow Leopard.

