00:14:06.200 --> 00:14:09.080
So next topic, system imaging.

00:14:09.110 --> 00:14:13.040
So how do you get these clients
that you want to manage with ARD,

00:14:13.090 --> 00:14:15.600
how do you get them
onto people's desktops?

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:18.280
So system imaging,
what do you use it for?

00:14:18.440 --> 00:14:21.020
Basically,
whatever source you have to create

00:14:21.060 --> 00:14:26.120
images from either DVD or user volume,
you use system image utility to

00:14:26.190 --> 00:14:29.320
create master images out of those,
either install sets or

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:32.060
volume restore sets.

00:14:32.060 --> 00:14:35.030
And then with server admin,
you have the tools that you

00:14:35.030 --> 00:14:36.600
can deploy these images with.

00:14:36.640 --> 00:14:40.840
So this, and you can finally customize
content with Package Maker.

00:14:40.900 --> 00:14:44.810
So if you have applications that
don't use the Apple installer

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:50.070
to deploy their packages with,
you have other tools available to you.

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:52.080
So what's new with the system imaging?

00:14:52.220 --> 00:14:56.230
So this covers what we have
new in Leopard or to be

00:14:56.260 --> 00:14:58.880
delivered in Snow Leopard.

00:14:58.960 --> 00:15:02.740
So with Mac OS X Leopard,
we basically rewrote the application.

00:15:02.790 --> 00:15:06.120
So now the application is
based on automated actions.

00:15:06.150 --> 00:15:09.780
So any step that you have
to do to create a image,

00:15:09.790 --> 00:15:13.200
either from volume or DVD,
is now an automated action.

00:15:13.280 --> 00:15:17.660
So you can use these workflows either
inside system image utility itself,

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:21.380
or you can use these in automated
workflows inside either automated

00:15:21.450 --> 00:15:25.200
application or other applications
that support workflows.

00:15:25.210 --> 00:15:28.440
And also, in addition to all these
powerful tools that you have,

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:30.700
we created a image assistant.

00:15:31.030 --> 00:15:35.180
So image assistant lets
you create really in one,

00:15:35.220 --> 00:15:37.920
two step,
create images that you can deploy

00:15:38.220 --> 00:15:42.380
without having to customize
or otherwise tweak the images.

00:15:42.400 --> 00:15:47.690
So it's really easy to use and
hopefully will let other people who

00:15:47.690 --> 00:15:52.860
are not necessarily that technically
savvy create their deployment sets.

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:56.580
And we also added pieces into
server admin where you can now

00:15:56.580 --> 00:16:00.810
monitor the status of either
systems that are installing an

00:16:00.810 --> 00:16:04.660
OS or doing a volume restore,
or you can see which systems

00:16:04.710 --> 00:16:06.340
are currently netbooted.

00:16:06.360 --> 00:16:10.160
And for load balancing,
we also added support for

00:16:10.160 --> 00:16:12.220
Exa and read-only volumes.

00:16:12.240 --> 00:16:14.360
So this would come in
handy where you have,

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:17.800
let's say multiple Exa's
acting as netboot servers,

00:16:17.800 --> 00:16:21.680
and you have Exa and volume
that's backing all the netboot

00:16:21.680 --> 00:16:25.170
images or netinstall images,
but on some Exa's,

00:16:25.480 --> 00:16:26.750
those volumes are read-only.

00:16:26.840 --> 00:16:30.170
So now we can actually offer netboot,
netinstall images off

00:16:30.270 --> 00:16:31.430
of read-only volumes.

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:36.730
Last but not least,
we now have ASR support inside

00:16:36.730 --> 00:16:39.650
system imaging in Snow Leopard.

00:16:39.740 --> 00:16:44.200
So this basically gives you
ASR multicast support or ASR sources

00:16:44.200 --> 00:16:46.620
such as HTTP disk images.

00:16:46.640 --> 00:16:49.250
And this is configured
via an automated action.

00:16:50.580 --> 00:16:55.500
So let me just give you a brief
look on how the tools look like.

00:16:55.500 --> 00:17:01.240
And here's the first thing you'd see
when you launch the system image utility.

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:03.520
So you land in the
Image Creation Assistant.

00:17:03.520 --> 00:17:05.620
And here we have just two sources.

00:17:05.620 --> 00:17:06.660
One is a volume source.

00:17:06.660 --> 00:17:08.500
One is a hard drive.

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:13.000
And you can create either net install
or netboot volumes from either

00:17:13.090 --> 00:17:16.500
install disk sets or the volume sets.

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:19.940
And what you can do then with the
workflow action-- so if you actually

00:17:19.940 --> 00:17:23.920
go on to customize these images,
first you can define where

00:17:23.920 --> 00:17:25.640
this image is created from.

00:17:25.640 --> 00:17:29.740
So you can pick an installation
type or an image type,

00:17:29.740 --> 00:17:33.340
either netboot or netinstall,
pick where it's created from.

00:17:33.340 --> 00:17:39.410
And if it's an install volume,
like you have a DVD at hand and you want

00:17:39.410 --> 00:17:44.300
to customize which packages are actually,
by default, delivered to your users,

00:17:44.300 --> 00:17:48.130
you can customize the package selection,
either entirely eliminating

00:17:48.130 --> 00:17:51.000
some packages so that they're
not selectable by the user,

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:56.000
or by changing the default set that the
user would get when they install this.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:01.000
So you can either add or delete options,
don't install all the printers,

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:04.930
only install some particular printers,
or don't install all languages.

00:18:05.020 --> 00:18:09.980
So that's a very flexible way
to customize the disk set.

00:18:10.220 --> 00:18:12.000
And you can also add packages.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.170
So if you do have application
packages such as Remote Desktop or

00:18:15.170 --> 00:18:19.000
other applications that come
bundled as a package model,

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:23.000
you can add those into your
installation set as well.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:29.330
And you can also add custom scripts that,
if there isn't a direct way to tweak some

00:18:29.330 --> 00:18:33.000
settings on the systems that you create,
you could use scripting,

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:37.000
shell scripts or Rubio, Perl, Python,
whatever have you,

00:18:37.150 --> 00:18:40.700
to finally lay down the bits that
you exactly need on the target

00:18:40.750 --> 00:18:43.000
systems just the way you'd like them.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:49.000
And for netboot images,
if we create those from

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.050
DVDs or DVD sources,
we have to create a

00:18:51.050 --> 00:18:54.000
user account for those,
so we have support for that.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.980
And we can also change some
of the system settings.

00:18:57.070 --> 00:19:00.000
So if we need to bind some of the
systems into directory systems,

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:04.000
we can configure that via the
system configuration settings.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:08.000
We can also rename some of the
systems based on their MAC addresses.

00:19:08.010 --> 00:19:13.040
So if you know that you have 15 machines
and they've all come up as Macintosh 1,

00:19:13.050 --> 00:19:15.000
2, 3, 4, that's not very helpful.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:18.920
So you could take down the MAC addresses
of the systems and actually call them

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
something that's meaningful to you.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:23.450
Or if you so choose,
you can just call them the

00:19:23.450 --> 00:19:28.000
Final Cut Lab 1-2-3 or 4.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:29.070
And then...

00:19:32.710 --> 00:19:37.720
You can also create installation
sets that effectively could

00:19:37.810 --> 00:19:39.600
wipe out your users hard drives.

00:19:39.710 --> 00:19:41.550
So this is for automated installation.

00:19:41.590 --> 00:19:43.940
This is useful for lab scenarios.

00:19:44.330 --> 00:19:49.190
Like if you have a lab or classroom
that has 50 to 100 machines,

00:19:49.250 --> 00:19:53.200
you'd rather not have to go one by
one to machine and click through

00:19:53.200 --> 00:19:55.100
all the panes for the installation.

00:19:55.150 --> 00:19:58.990
But if you know that your target
machines will have some known

00:19:59.620 --> 00:20:02.680
elements such as a named hard drive,
you could fork off the

00:20:02.680 --> 00:20:05.110
installation based on that and say,
well,

00:20:05.150 --> 00:20:10.320
if I see a hard drive called erase me,
then just go ahead with the installation

00:20:10.320 --> 00:20:14.280
and wipe out the target and lay down
the bits without you having to do

00:20:14.320 --> 00:20:16.040
anything on the machines themselves.

00:20:16.100 --> 00:20:20.280
So the next time the systems come up,
they'll actually be booted into the

00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:22.830
installation that you just finished.

00:20:22.870 --> 00:20:27.250
and another system deployment or
system configuration setting we

00:20:27.250 --> 00:20:29.290
have is for partition in the disk.

00:20:29.340 --> 00:20:32.120
So you may want to change
the disk configuration,

00:20:32.120 --> 00:20:36.060
for example, adding a bootcamp partition
on the target systems.

00:20:36.060 --> 00:20:38.330
So you can also-- not only
can you just erase the hard

00:20:38.330 --> 00:20:41.870
drive and lay down new bits,
you can also reconfigure the disks

00:20:41.910 --> 00:20:44.180
into partitions that you'd like to see.

00:20:44.180 --> 00:20:48.830
You might have two partitions for
the OS and another partition for

00:20:48.830 --> 00:20:51.660
user data depending on your needs.

00:20:53.760 --> 00:20:55.940
And we also support
filtering for the images.

00:20:55.940 --> 00:20:59.940
So some images are not
applicable to all Mac clients.

00:21:00.020 --> 00:21:03.400
So you might have installed images
that are applicable to only,

00:21:03.530 --> 00:21:04.970
let's say, Mac Pros.

00:21:05.060 --> 00:21:09.200
So if you do create a
Final Cut application bundle

00:21:09.380 --> 00:21:12.080
that's an install set,
you may not want to offer

00:21:12.080 --> 00:21:16.140
that to a iMac or MacBook,
but you may want to restrict

00:21:16.250 --> 00:21:18.350
that only into Mac Pros.

00:21:18.420 --> 00:21:22.050
And you can also filter the
images based on Mac addresses.

00:21:22.220 --> 00:21:27.740
So if you know that you're testing an
image that you will deploy down the road,

00:21:27.740 --> 00:21:30.500
but you really want to serve it
from your production service,

00:21:30.550 --> 00:21:35.190
you can set the image settings so that
they're only available to particular

00:21:35.240 --> 00:21:39.770
set of machines that you want to
use for your deployment testing.

00:21:41.260 --> 00:21:43.730
and finally,
we have a create image where you

00:21:43.730 --> 00:21:47.340
can define where this image will be
stored and what it will be called.

00:21:47.350 --> 00:21:49.800
And what's new to Snow Leopard then?

00:21:49.840 --> 00:21:55.610
This is the action where you configure
the ASR multicast restore source.

00:21:55.720 --> 00:22:00.700
So either ASR multicast streams
or HTTP images stored on a

00:22:00.780 --> 00:22:03.680
server can be defined here.

00:22:03.710 --> 00:22:07.410
And you also have options to
discover the restore sources

00:22:07.530 --> 00:22:09.140
dynamically on the network.

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:13.430
So if you create a disk
image that doesn't have any

00:22:13.430 --> 00:22:17.950
ASR sources defined in it,
the client can discover these sources

00:22:18.120 --> 00:22:19.940
when it's actually on the network.

00:22:19.960 --> 00:22:24.500
And you'd send a Bonjour beacon
on the network advertising the

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:26.440
availability of restore sources.

00:22:26.490 --> 00:22:30.250
So if you start up a multicast stream,
the restore image will automatically

00:22:30.330 --> 00:22:34.230
pick that up and you could select
that as your restore source.

00:22:34.390 --> 00:22:37.560
So this is new to Snow Leopard
and will be part of the

00:22:37.640 --> 00:22:39.150
Mac OS X Snow Leopard package.

00:22:39.160 --> 00:22:42.360
And then Packagemaker.

00:22:42.360 --> 00:22:44.740
So this is not necessarily
part of system imaging as such,

00:22:44.780 --> 00:22:49.550
but quite a few people have not
really used the tool and some people

00:22:49.550 --> 00:22:51.880
don't know what to do with that.

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:54.020
Well,
one interesting thing with Packagemaker

00:22:54.040 --> 00:22:58.190
is the remote source for packages.

00:22:58.340 --> 00:23:02.560
So with Packagemaker in Mac OS X Leopard,
you can actually source the

00:23:02.980 --> 00:23:07.310
data payload for your install
images off of a web server.

00:23:07.430 --> 00:23:09.150
So imagine that you
create an application,

00:23:09.240 --> 00:23:11.630
you create a new installer
that installs the latest,

00:23:11.710 --> 00:23:16.200
let's say Firefox or could
be Office or could be CS3.

00:23:16.210 --> 00:23:19.300
And you know that, well,
this is up to date for today.

00:23:19.320 --> 00:23:23.040
And maybe there's gonna be an update
down the road that you'd want to install,

00:23:23.170 --> 00:23:26.120
but you'd rather not go back to
the initial disk set and have

00:23:26.190 --> 00:23:27.590
to recreate it all from scratch.

00:23:27.730 --> 00:23:31.290
So with Packagemaker,
you can actually point to the network

00:23:31.290 --> 00:23:36.210
live copy of the installation set and
that would be always kept up to date.

00:23:36.290 --> 00:23:40.320
So no matter when you install this,
this system,

00:23:40.350 --> 00:23:43.540
you'll always get the latest,
most current version of applications that

00:23:43.540 --> 00:23:46.840
are using the web-based package payloads.

00:23:46.870 --> 00:23:50.180
So that's definitely something that
will be useful for deployments.

00:23:50.180 --> 00:23:54.920
And, yay, go Packagemaker.

00:23:55.090 --> 00:23:58.640
and where you'd actually access
this in system image utility is

00:23:58.810 --> 00:24:01.800
through the add packages action.

00:24:01.800 --> 00:24:05.560
So you can add to the
remotely stored packages,

00:24:05.560 --> 00:24:09.640
the pointer to that will be contained
in a standard package that you add,

00:24:09.730 --> 00:24:13.240
but then the payload itself will
be carried down at a later stage.

