00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:00.900
Okay, portable home directories,
mobile accounts, external accounts,

00:42:01.030 --> 00:42:05.150
what they're all about is taking
a network account and the whole

00:42:05.150 --> 00:42:08.500
user's home directory and making them
portable so that the user can log

00:42:08.500 --> 00:42:12.510
in and use that home directory when
they're not connected to the network.

00:42:13.680 --> 00:42:19.970
Also, when we talk about the account,
all the management of the

00:42:19.970 --> 00:42:23.490
account goes with these users.

00:42:23.490 --> 00:42:23.490
So this is a good way to manage
a local user as a network user.

00:42:24.870 --> 00:42:28.580
Mac OS 10.3 Panther was where
we introduced mobile accounts.

00:42:28.760 --> 00:42:31.490
At that time,
we had a mobile account with a

00:42:31.490 --> 00:42:34.300
cached account with credentials
so you could log in offline.

00:42:34.360 --> 00:42:37.680
But the home directory that
you created locally did not

00:42:37.680 --> 00:42:41.180
synchronize with the network home.

00:42:41.480 --> 00:42:45.800
In Mac OS 10.4 Tiger,
we introduced portable home directories

00:42:45.880 --> 00:42:49.160
and that really is all the things of a
mobile account plus home synchronization.

00:42:49.280 --> 00:42:55.460
So now, in Tiger,
you can create a portable home directory,

00:42:55.570 --> 00:42:59.070
take your portable computer,
use it offline, make all sorts of changes

00:42:59.070 --> 00:43:01.340
to your home directory,
come back to the network and

00:43:01.340 --> 00:43:04.370
it will synchronize all the
changes you made locally back up

00:43:04.370 --> 00:43:06.030
to your network home directory.

00:43:06.200 --> 00:43:10.130
Starting in Leopard,
we introduced external accounts and more.

00:43:10.220 --> 00:43:15.110
An external account is a mobile account,
is a portable home directory,

00:43:15.110 --> 00:43:18.310
but instead of living on the
internal disk of a computer,

00:43:18.310 --> 00:43:19.570
it lives on a disk itself.

00:43:19.600 --> 00:43:23.080
So the disk itself contains
the account information and it

00:43:23.080 --> 00:43:25.090
contains the home directory.

00:43:25.150 --> 00:43:28.330
Now I said and more there
because as we progress from 10.3,

00:43:28.330 --> 00:43:31.390
10.4, 10.5,
we've been adding more management

00:43:31.860 --> 00:43:35.700
features so now you can really
control home directory creation

00:43:35.700 --> 00:43:38.590
and synchronization very finely.

00:43:39.870 --> 00:43:42.530
So here's some new management
things we put in for portable

00:43:42.530 --> 00:43:43.840
home directories in Leopard.

00:43:44.010 --> 00:43:45.820
First of all, FileVault.

00:43:45.850 --> 00:43:48.340
Starting in Leopard,
you can require that FileVault that

00:43:48.340 --> 00:43:55.270
when a user creates a mobile account,
that the home directory will

00:43:55.510 --> 00:43:57.040
be protected by FileVault.

00:43:57.170 --> 00:44:00.420
FileVault is essentially an
encrypted file system for just

00:44:00.470 --> 00:44:02.120
the user's home directory.

00:44:02.160 --> 00:44:05.130
So protect the information in there so
that you can't get in there without an

00:44:05.130 --> 00:44:08.210
account password or a master password.

00:44:08.640 --> 00:44:11.930
Starting in Leopard,
the account can now be on an internal

00:44:11.960 --> 00:44:17.680
or an external hard disk as well as just
under the users folder of the boot disk.

00:44:17.720 --> 00:44:23.600
And when it's on an external disk,
we call that an external account.

00:44:24.700 --> 00:44:26.780
We added account expiration.

00:44:26.880 --> 00:44:30.380
So what this is is that if you
set up mobile accounts across

00:44:30.380 --> 00:44:33.710
your network and you have a
whole bunch of network machines,

00:44:33.710 --> 00:44:36.600
one day a user will come into
machine A and they'll log in and

00:44:36.600 --> 00:44:39.720
because of the management settings
they'll create a PhD there and

00:44:39.720 --> 00:44:41.460
they'll be happy and log off,
sync back to the network.

00:44:41.840 --> 00:44:44.040
They come back on another day,
they log into machine B,

00:44:44.040 --> 00:44:46.110
they get another mobile account,
they get the fresh

00:44:46.230 --> 00:44:47.940
information from the network,
they log off,

00:44:48.050 --> 00:44:50.030
they sync back to the network,
they're happy.

00:44:50.080 --> 00:44:53.000
They go to another machine,
third day and you can see what happens.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:56.660
By the end of the week they've got a
mobile account on all these different

00:44:56.660 --> 00:44:58.580
machines and they're taking up resources.

00:44:58.580 --> 00:45:03.580
So starting in Leopard you can now have
these accounts be reaped and deleted or

00:45:03.600 --> 00:45:07.990
expired after a certain amount of unuse.

00:45:09.410 --> 00:45:13.850
Okay, we also added MCX and
HomeSync preference manifests.

00:45:13.930 --> 00:45:16.620
Okay, now you can actually have quite
a bit of fine-grained control

00:45:16.620 --> 00:45:18.090
over PHG creation and sync.

00:45:18.110 --> 00:45:22.130
A whole bunch of keys are now exposed
so that you can actually change

00:45:22.210 --> 00:45:25.900
things to your own site requirements.

00:45:25.930 --> 00:45:28.060
We added a sync server.

00:45:28.110 --> 00:45:31.400
A synchronization server is a process
which runs an OS X server and it

00:45:31.400 --> 00:45:34.660
keeps listening to the FS event queue.

00:45:34.670 --> 00:45:36.470
And so you have to think about
how a synchronization works.

00:45:36.660 --> 00:45:38.520
How a synchronization works
is there's two big phases.

00:45:38.600 --> 00:45:42.100
One is you figure out what's changed
and the second one is you copy stuff.

00:45:42.180 --> 00:45:45.160
And it turns out that figuring out
what's changed can usually take

00:45:45.230 --> 00:45:48.490
more time than the data that's
copied because prior to using the

00:45:48.610 --> 00:45:51.820
synchronization server in Tiger,
you had to walk through the entire

00:45:51.920 --> 00:45:54.490
folder hierarchy and do this big
enumerate on the server and locally

00:45:54.590 --> 00:45:55.990
to figure out what's changed.

00:45:56.100 --> 00:45:59.390
Starting in Leopard,
we used a sync server so this figuring

00:45:59.390 --> 00:46:04.310
out what's changed phase is much quicker
and so the entire synchronization

00:46:04.810 --> 00:46:07.090
process is much quicker as well.

