can specify a sync URL and that's a

00:51:25.830 --> 00:51:29.200
URL like afp:// that sort of thing.

00:51:29.200 --> 00:51:33.860
And that allows you to have a
mobile account which synchronizes

00:51:33.860 --> 00:51:37.200
to not just to its network home,
but perhaps it can synchronize to

00:51:37.230 --> 00:51:40.190
another file server completely or a
different spot on the network home.

00:51:40.200 --> 00:51:44.810
I was talking to an Active Directory user
site and they wanted to have their

00:51:44.870 --> 00:51:49.200
Leopard clients synchronized to a
folder inside their network home.

00:51:49.200 --> 00:51:51.770
So if you create it with the
create mobile account tool,

00:51:51.770 --> 00:51:53.200
it will allow you to do that.

00:51:53.200 --> 00:51:57.240
Another trick, which you only hear
about at WWDC I think,

00:51:57.320 --> 00:52:00.530
is that if you have an existing loader,
if you have a local account and

00:52:00.530 --> 00:52:03.210
